- INSTALATION

- Install ruby

    - $ sudo apt-get install ruby-full
- Install gems

    - $rvm rubygems current
- Install rails

    - $gem install rails - http://railsinstaller.org/en
- Create a new app

    - $rails new app_name

- GEM FILES

Should always be in the root directory. A gem is a collection of Ruby code that we can extract into a “collection” which we can call later.
Contain methods signatures, suggestion of implementations created by other developers and are inside the GEM FILE.
Install local gems while suppressing the installation of production gems using the --without production option:
$ bundle install --without production

          3.CREATE REPOSITORIES

-- Commit app - bitbucket
$ git init
$ git add -A
$ git commit -m "Initialize repository"

-- Create repository
$ git remote add origin git@bitbucket.org:<username>/toy_app.git
$ git push -u origin --all
or
$ git push master
$ git checkout branchname

-  CREATE DATABASE

Download postgresql
www.enterprisedb.com/crossover-thankyou
Run commands
chmod +x file-name.run
./file-name.run

Update database.yml file
default: &default
  adapter: posgresql
  database: mydb
  username: postgres
  password: SabeNada@#$28
  pool: 5
  timeout: 5000

Run $gem install pg
Open your gem file
Comment sqllite3
Add gem 'pg'

Run $bundle install

     5. HEROKU
1. Create a free account
2. Download https://toolbelt.heroku.com/install-ubuntu.sh
3. Setup a database
4. Create git repository
5. Push and deploy the app via heroku

- GENERATE  CONTROLLERS

--Generate controller
rails generate controller home index

- ROUTES

open config > routes.rb
root :to <<put your home page>>

